  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy was a system of government introduced in India through the Government of India Act, 1919 (also known as the Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms). Here are the key details:\n\n1. Introduction:\n- Implemented in 1921\n- Introduced by the British government to provide limited self-governance in provinces\n\n2. Key Features:\n- Division of provincial government into two spheres:\na) Reserved subjects (controlled by British governors)\nb) Transferred subjects (controlled by Indian ministers)\n\n3. Reserved Subjects:\n- Finance\n- Revenue\n- Law and order\n- Police\n- Justice\n- Army\n\n4. Transferred Subjects:\n- Education\n- Public Health\n- Local Self-Government\n- Agriculture\n- Cooperative Societies\n\n5. Objectives:\n- Gradual introduction of self-governance\n- Increasing Indian participation in governance\n- Preparing Indians for eventual responsible government\n\n6. Criticism:\n- Limited political power for Indians\n- Complex administrative structure\n- Potential for conflicts between reserved and transferred subjects\n\nThe dyarchy system was eventually replaced by the Government of India Act, 1935, which introduced more substantial provincial autonomy.",
